<TEXT>
it didnt reach the goose that laid the 
golden egg but for 31 years a man named jack grew and grew and 
grew a philodendron until it could be stretched the length of nearly 
four football fields 
the vine reached his living room ceiling and wound up down and 
around itself at christmas time he strung colored lights from it 
while it kept on growing until it reached a record 1114 feet 
and then in 1984 jack francis chopped it down 
it was a bit of a sentimental moment because it had been 
around so long i bought it as a little sprout in sears when we 
first moved to amherst the university of massachusetts professor 
said 
but sentiment aside francis said he was forced to fell his 
prized philodendron 
that was the only way we could measure it for the record and 
to tell you the truth i was getting a bit tired of it he said 
chopped into fourfoot lengths it stacked up like cordwood 
his children persuaded him to submit it to the guinness book of 
world records and years later he and his plant are still enjoying 
their day in the sun 
i did it as a joke and no one was more surprised than i when 
they accepted it francis said and if id only realized the 
sort of attention it would get id at at least have taken a proper 
picture of it 
but jacks stalk weighed about 250 pounds and dragging it into a 
welllighted spot seemed overwhelming so the photo opportunity was 
missed 
francis walls are lined with plaques commending him for his 
academic achievements in the field of food science and nutrition 
but that acclaim has been shaded by his gardening success 
despite all this francis said gesturing to the citations 
what im known for to everybody is growing the worlds largest 
philodendron 
the key to growing the worlds largest philodendron the 
previous mark had been 600 feet is patience francis said 
other than fertilizing every time he watered and winding it back 
around itself francis took no special steps 
one of the problems i had though was repotting it he said 
they only make pots so big and it had pretty much reached the 
maximum and there wasnt much dirt left when we cut it down 
but thats the way jacks garden grows his late tomato plants 
were already a thick lush 7foot hedge the first week in july when 
most new england gardeners are nursing along 2 and 3foot plants 
he also grows dozens of varieties of vegetables ranging from the 
common zucchini to such southern exotics as passion fruit kiwi and 
chayote 
his 50by70foot garden got so dense that a few years back when 
he was a semifinalist in the annual gardening contest run by 
pbstvs victory garden the cameras couldnt get into the rows 
i dont have the space for them to grow horizontally so they 
have to grow up francis said this is my latest experiment and 
sweet potatoes dont like growing up at all i have to tuck them 
back in the cage every day 
