the clinic has come under numerous attacks since ragsdale moved 
his practice to there four years ago after a hospital affiliate 
refused to renew his lease because of the high cost of making the 
building improvements required by the state for abortion clinics 
at least 180 people have been arrested for trespassing seven 
people have been arrested for battery and five fires have been set 
said the buildings owner wayne webster a suspect in at least two 
of the arson fires has been convicted and jailed 
its hard to picture a less likely site for such a battle 
the twostory limestoneandbrick structure is in a modest 
commercial district inside three tenants are organizations that 
hold bingo parties in a downstairs hall where wooden floors creak 
and chalk boards line the walls 
upstairs ragsdales clinic occupies onetenth of the building 
and has a 10year lease the renovated 4000squarefoot complex 
has a sophisticated security system with audio and visual monitors 
to keep track of protesters outside 
the clinic is open three mornings a week and says it serves 12 
to 30 patients daily almost all of whom receive abortions 
eightyfive percent are referred by other physicians or by 
womens healthcare centers said ragsdale who testified in 1985 
