<TEXT>
jurors are being asked to solve a mystery that 
has baffled medical investigators for four years the source of the 
deadly bacteria that got into a batch of cheese and killed 48 people 
the panel after hearing conflicting expert testimony must 
decide whether altadena certified dairy should share liability with 
the defunct jalisco mexican products inc for some 100 million in 
victims claims stemming from a 1985 listeriosis outbreak 
more than 100 lawsuits have been filed on behalf of the 18 
stricken adults and 30 infants and stillborn fetuses from one of the 
nations deadliest foodtransmitted epidemics the federal centers 
for disease control in atlanta counted 142 cases of listeriosis from 
jan 1 to aug 15 1985 the epidemic left some survivors with birth 
defects 
altadena the largest dairy in california supplied the raw milk 
to jalisco to make the soft mexicanstyle cheese which was blamed 
for the outbreak of the severe flulike bacterial disease 
victims want altadena to share responsibility for the outbreak 
due to the limited nature of funds available for jalisco a 
number of people involved in litigation are not going to get full 
compensation for their injuries and the death of loved ones unless 
altadena is found responsible said lawyer kimberlee miller 
the trial began three weeks ago in superior judge richard 
lavines courtroom and testimony is expected to conclude this week 
testimony thus far has failed to clarify whether the 
contamination came from altadenas raw milk or from sloppy 
pasteurization and dirty conditions at the jalisco plant 
altadena sold to jalisco a product that contained listeria 
monocytogenese and altadena is partly responsible for this 
epidemic jalisco attorney roy brisbois said in opening statements 
a key witness for jalisco agreed 
we believe the source of the listeriosis outbreak was raw 
milk said epidemiologist laurene mascola a former cdc employee 
stationed in los angeles at the time of the epidemic 
but dairy lawyer raymond novell told the jury that bacteria was 
never found in altadena milk or dairy herds and noted that 
altadena supplied 26 million gallons of milk to its customers 
during the period and only jalisco had the listeriosis outbreak 
the bacteria was found in abundance in refrigerators ants and 
even in the bodies of employees at the jalisco plant he said 
there is no mystery here the mystery is solved if you look at 
the jalisco plant said novell proper pasteurization there would 
have killed the listeria bacteria he said 
jalisco cheese maker jose luis medina conceded under 
crossexamination that he had allowed unlicensed employees to 
pasteurize raw milk the listeria bacteria is killed in the 
pasteurization process 
medina and jalisco owner gary mcpherson pleaded no contest in 
1986 to misdemeanor criminal charges mcpherson was sentenced to 30 
days in jail and medina was sentenced to 60 days they were fined 
about 48000 
listeria bacteria are common in the environment but cause 
illness mainly in people with immature or damaged immune systems 
such as babies elderly people and aids and cancer patients 
listeriosis is fatal about 30 percent of the time but can produce 
mild to severe flulike symptoms including fever abdominal pain 
headaches and nausea 
a separate jury will determine the extent of financial liability 
if the jury finds altadena partially responsible for the outbreak 
numerous separate trials are expected to follow 
