president bush today became the first 
american leader to address the polish national assembly the 
communist worlds only parliament with a freely elected opposition 
party 
nearly half the legislators are supporters of the independent 
solidarity trade union movement who were seated july 4 following the 
east blocs freest elections in four decades 
the national assembly is the result of unprecedented april 
accords reached by communist authorities and the solidarityled 
opposition the agreement created a senate which combined with the 
existing sejm or parliament to form the national assembly 
the pact which lifted a sevenyear ban on solidarity allowed 
independent candidates to contest all 100 senate seats and 161 
places in the 460seat sejm 
solidarity swept 99 of the senate seats and 161 places in the 
sejm in junes twostage vote 
already there is a new style at the white building on a bluff 
above the vistula river opposition deputies have electrified the 
once sleepy sejm with harsh attacks on government policy 
sejm deputy janusz onyszkiewicz who doubles as national 
spokesman for solidarity often rides his bike to parliament deputy 
adam michnik editor of the opposition daily gazeta wyborcza so far 
has declined to discard his blue jeans 
seating for the bush speech was tight because the main chamber 
was designed to accommodate only the sejm 
but the large wooden chair for the president of poland a new 
post created by the april accords was empty authorities had hoped 
to have the president elected in time for the bush visit but the 
failure of the communist party to designate a candidate delayed the 
vote by the joint sejm and senate 
poles arent quite used to the name national assembly and the 
building is still commonly referred to as the sejm a word first 
used in the middle ages 
in polish the word sejm means assembly or council founded on 
the basis of local sejms polands first national bicameral sejm was 
convened in 1493 
in contrast to much of europe which was ruled by hereditary 
royalty poland had an elected king chosen by the sejm which 
consisted of nobles the sejm was able to check the kings power 
with its right to veto proposals 
but polands democracy ended when the crowns of austria prussia 
and russia partitioned the country among themselves in 1795 
the first modern sejm convened in 1919 after poland reappeared 
on the map of europe following germanys defeat in world war i 
parliament met in a girls school until a proper home could be built 
in 1928 
the 1939 nazi and soviet invasions of poland smothered the 
countrys democratic revival the sejm was razed during the war 
like much of the capital 
democratic elections were agreed upon in principle by the allied 
powers at the end of world war ii when the soviet red army occupied 
poland 
the 1947 elections were denounced in the west as a sham but the 
results left communists firmly in control of parliament and the 
party then rewrote the laws to preclude any real political 
opposition 
the national assembly sworn in july 4 is the first with 
opposition representation in eastern europe since the late 1940s 
under the agreement negotiaed by the communist government and the 
opposition the sejm initiates legislation and the senate holds veto 
power 
the sejm can override a senate veto only with a twothirds 
majority a margin the communist coalition lacks therefore all 
legislation will require approval of solidaritybacked lawmakers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

