<TEXT>
thousands of iranians turned out for an 
antisaudi arabia rally monday the second anniversary of fatal 
riots by iranians in mecca and irans president said saudi 
government officials were terrorists 
the developments deepened a growing rift between irans shiite 
moslem government and the sunni rulers of saudi arabia as both 
countries prepared for major religious events this week 
the saudi regime which massacres in cold blood hundreds of 
pilgrims near allahs safe house is a terrorist tehrans official 
islamic republic news agency quoted president ali khamenei as saying 
saudi officials say iranian fundamentalists caused the july 10 
1987 riots in which more than 400 mostly iranian protesters died 
iran says its pilgrims were exercising their legitimate right to a 
political protest in mecca birthplace of the prophet mohammed 
in saudi arabia on monday king fahd called for heightened 
security around the annual moslem pilgrimage or hajj to the 
shrines in mecca and medina apparently fearing iranianinstigated 
trouble 
tehran television monitored in nicosia showed thousands of 
iranians converging on the imam hussein square in downtown tehran 
chanting mecca and medina should be liberated 
thursday marks the end of the 40day mourning period for 
ayatollah ruhollah khomeini who died june 3 the planned final mass 
outpouring of grief at his grave coincides with the climax of the 
pilgrimage in saudi arabia the eid aladha or feast of sacrifice 
iran claims the pilgrimage is being corrupted and has boycotted 
it for the second straight year 
last year the saudi government also introduced a quota system 
limiting the number of pilgrims to 1000 per million of population 
effectively cutting the usual iranian contingent of 150000 to about 
50000 
fahds call for tighter security came days after a saudi 
editorial rebuked iran for introducing politics into a religious 
festival and for keeping its people away from the hajj one of the 
five duties of all moslems 
saudi arabia severed relations with tehran in april last year 
citing subversion and terrorism 
the shiitesunni rift evolved from the bloody 7th century fight 
over who would succeed mohammed founder of islam as leader of the 
religion 
