<TEXT>
sophisticated blood testing techniques 
developed by the centers for disease control will enable scientists 
to provide better data on whether agent orange sprayed on trees in 
vietnam is having adverse health effects on veterans a panel of 
experts told a house subcommittee monday 
controversy has ranged for years over whether the government is 
responsible for a variety of health problems reported by vietnam 
veterans who assert their problems were caused by exposure to agent 
orange 
a majority of scientists maintain there is no established link 
between the kind of exposure to dioxin that occurred in vietnam and 
health hazards 
on the other hand veterans groups argue there is no other 
explanation for cancers and birth defects reported by vietnam 
veterans 
a panel appearing before the veterans affairs hospitals and 
health care subcommittee agreed that the blood test now being used 
to measure dioxin levels in the blood gives researchers a better 
tool to determine whether people who fear they suffered 
healththreatening exposure to dioxin actually did so 
dioxin is the main ingredient in agent orange and has been linked 
to various cancers and birth defects in rats although not 
conclusively in humans 
dr vernon n houk director of the center for environmental 
health and injury control at the atlantabased cdc told the 
subcommittee the test developed about three years and just now 
coming into wide use can detect dioxin in the blood of farm 
workers who have not been exposed to the chemical in 30 years and 
thus will be an accurate measure of exposure levels in vietnam 
veterans 
houk said development of the test made a whole new ball game 
for us it really let us clarify how much people were exposed 
he said the cdc is in the process of applying the test to 2000 
blood samples of vietnam veterans and will be finished by next 
march when it expects to issue a definitive report 
he said the test costs about 1000 for each sample and that his 
staff of 16 can perform about 50 a week 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

