<TEXT>
a poison control center physician said monday 
she knows of 19 children who have swallowed batteries from the new 
ghostblaster toy offered by hardees restaurants as a 
promotional gimmick tied to the ghostbuster ii movie 
at company headquarters in rocky mount nc hardees said it 
was altering the 2 million remaining toys to seal the battery 
compartments and strengthen package warnings 
dr toby litovitz medical director of the capital poison control 
center at georgetown university hospital said 19 calls have been 
received by the centers hotline over a 10day period about children 
between 1 and 3 years old swallowing the button batteries that 
operate the toys 
the center receives calls from all over the country including 
from other hospitalbased poison control centers 
calls from anxious parents have come from everywhere and this 
is just the tip of the iceberg she said 
she said she believed based on past experience that as many as 
100 more incidents have gone unreported 
hardees restaurants began offering the promotional toys june 28 
allowing patrons who purchase a meal or a dessert to buy the small 
rectangle noisemaker in one of four colors for 179 the toy comes 
in red black white or gray and makes one of two different kinds of 
noise to send away the ghost 
hardees distributed 2 million of the toys in a week and has 2 
million more on hand said john merritt vice president for public 
affairs of hardees 
hardees officials decided not enough attention was being paid to 
posted warnings that the toys were not appropriate for children 
under age 3 merritt said 
little 6yearold johnny which this toy is designed for 
leaves it lying around and his little brother gets it open and eats 
the battery he said 
hardees informed the consumer product safety commission of the 
problem and agreed to place similar warnings directly on the plastic 
cases sealing the battery compartments at the same time he said 
merritt said the company knew of no injuries associated with 
swallowing the batteries 
every year at christmas children ingest all kinds of small 
parts and are none the worse for wear he said but its not 
good for you 
merritt said anyone who already has a ghostblaster can return 
it to any restaurant to have it altered 
officials of the consumer product safety commission said they 
were discussing an announcement about the toy with the company 
dr litovitz said the center averages about 400 button battery 
ingestion cases a year but never so many from a single product 
its not an issue for hysteria because the batteries usually 
pass through without a problem said dr litovitz 
the small batteries also can be put into noses and ears causing 
hearing loss or facial deformity she cautioned 
she said parents should seek medical attention immediately for 
any child swallowing a battery if the battery becomes lodged in the 
esophagus there is a risk of perforation and death she said 
chemicals leaking from the battery could cause severe burns to 
the esophagus she said 
