<TEXT>
after 16 years of authoritarian military 
rule chileans are getting instruction on how to live in democracy 
and preserve it after a civilian government takes over in march 
we are convinced that democracy can only survive in chile and 
latin america if all citizens take good care of it said monica 
jimenez director of a 350000 nonpartisan educational project 
called participate citizens must understand that democracy is not 
only a government system but also a lifestyle 
from that principle comes participates motto democracy 
everybodys responsability 
financing for the project was provided by the costa ricabased 
interamerican institute for human rights 
mrs jimenez a university professor and social worker directed 
a similar program last year called crusade for citizen 
participation which won her an award from the national endowment 
for democracy in washington dc 
that crusade mobilized 200000 volunteers across the country in a 
doortodoor campaign to promote voter registration for octobers 
referendum in which voters rejected a military proposal to extend 
until 1997 the presidency of gen augusto pinochet who took power 
in a 1973 coup 
the referendum obliged pinochet to call an open presidential 
election which will be held dec 14 pinochet is due to hand over 
power to the winner march 11 
it will be chiles first civilian government since the coup and 
mrs jimenez says chileans especially younger ones must be helped 
to face their new life under democracy and most of all to 
preserve it 
chile and latin america have gone through longlasting military 
dictatorships which created an atmosphere of confrontation within 
our societies she said in an interview 
we have been split among friends and enemies so we have now to 
create a new atmosphere where we all act as friends a society where 
we can have different opinions on many issues and still be able to 
sit around a table and talk and reach agreements 
in other words we have been able to realize that the other guy 
may also have part of truth 
mrs jimenez stressed that the program is completely 
nonpartisan 
we have some members of political parties working with us and 
we are also working with the catholic and other christian 
churches she said but they are all committed not to let their 
political or regligious beliefs interfere 
participate has already trained 400 civic educators to 
conduct the program those educators have trained about 3000 aids 
to work with them 
their job is to lecture a wide variety of groups in our 
society mrs jimenez said 
reaction has so far been very good requests for our lecturers 
are piling up from labor unions religious groups neighbors and 
housewives organizations sports and social clubs 
the workers are all volunteers and are picked mostly from among 
university students and young professionals 
