<TEXT>
fashionwatchers from new york to tokyo have been 
spotting battalions of quilted chain bags gold buttons and 
braidpiped suits all familiar chanel symbols 
you might even see a hairy man wearing a chanel tshirt an 
incongruous offshoot of the newest wave of the chanel cult 
coco chanel died in 1971 but her designs never seem to go 
out of style and imitators have scrambled to make hay from the 
recent boom the plethora of fakes infuriates the house of chanel 
currently suing copyists right and left 
but as chanel said my ideas belong to everyone and the 
chanel craze goes on apace 
nowadays the chanel look connotes both status and chic even 
when runway shows are updated with wild departures from the old 
formulas by the houses designer karl lagerfeld 
in her heyday chanel was a revolutionary at a time when 
proper postvictorians were still gussied up in feathers and 
corsets chanel was busy ridding clothes of extraneous trappings 
stripping them down to the basics then dressing them up with pearls 
born in 1883 to a poor family in central france gabrielle chanel 
worked her way to the top as she discovered high society through her 
lovers 
her lifelong sobriquet of coco came from a song cocorico 
cockadoodledo she sang at a music hall in vichy clever with 
her hands she loved dressing up in her own homemade costumes 
by 1913 an english admirer named boy capel had set her up in 
a milliners shop in fashionable deauville 
too proud to imitate the wealthy women she met chanel set her 
own styles and soon everyone was copying her pareddown elegance 
her jaunty boater hats her middycollared dresses 
other designers like poiret and vionnet were loosening up on 
their clothes by 1914 when world war i began but it was coco who 
best caught the spirit of the jazz age she openly flouted 
conventions at a time when other women began wanting more freedom 
and her clothes suited the new mood 
women flocked in from the ritz across the street when she opened 
her shop in the rue cambon in 1919 as the twenties roared in to the 
charleston chanel with her relaxed assured manner and clothes to 
match had an instant success as she put it i woke up famous 
her own best model she shortened her skirts wore long cardigans 
with pockets and bobbed her long hair masses of women followed 
suit 
she pioneered pants for women with flowing pajamas worn by garbo 
and dietrich on the flickering screen she made the little black 
dress a glamour item with many strands of imitation pearls 
always mademoiselle to her staff she never married any of 
the celebrated men who courted her if her heart was broken she was 
unbowed toiling on as a ceaseless perfectionist 
after world war ii chanel moved to switzerland where she kept 
company with a german officer 
her attempted comeback in 1954 met with sullen press commentary 
diors 1947 new look sensation had still not worn off and the 
fashion mavens wanted more exciting news than chanels quiet little 
suits brought 
but chanel didnt stay long in the shade the time was ripe for 
her outfits which were both comfortable and glamorous without 
looking stiffly sophisticated 
women in the street were tiring of the new look and loved 
chanels style especially the braidedged suits with quilted 
linings 
by the time she died at 87 she had twice won and then held her 
place at the top of the fashion heap the house of chanel coasted on 
her old models and reputation until 1983 when germanborn lagerfeld 
came sweeping in like a bracing blast of fresh air and chanel was 
hot news again 
lagerfelds odder innovations like 18thcenturystyle panniers 
have shaken up some steadfast chanel fans 
but theres always an identifiable chanel suit in the collections 
to please conservatives and lagerfeld has blown up chanel details 
chains pearls the crossed c logo into a fetish that borders on 
high camp 
he sees the current craze as suited to todays rock culture in 
the chains and leather allied to the chanel cachet which is a 
passport for respectability 
chanel accessories simply work says ellin saltzman fashion 
director of saks fifth avenue in new york the bags hang right on 
your shoulder and the chains and buttons dress up anything 
working women love chanel as it is both serious and 
femininelooking fashion exaggeration like baby doll and vamp 
looks dont go down well in an office says chantal clayeux a 
french government employee chanel does 
the best of chanel looks right in almost any situation as coco 
chanel herself once observed an elegant woman must be able to do 
the marketing without making the other housewives laugh the ones 
who laugh are always right 
</TEXT>
