<DOCNO> AP890710-0241 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
like the storybook awakening of rip van winkle who 
found hed slept into old age western european nations are 
discovering what it means to lose their youth 
parts of europe already have the worlds highest populations of 
elderly people and governments are recognizing the change 
especially in the fasteraging north where retirees may comprise 40 
percent of some populations by 2040 from west germany to greece 
countries are studying how fewer young people will support strained 
pension and health care systems 
but gloomy visions of crowded oldage homes and broken economies 
are out of line experts say they worry about the poor and lonely 
but say most will be comfortable with money to spend as 
advertisers have already noticed 
the challenge experts say will be to show society that age 
doesnt mean illness or empty lives no americanstyle gray panthers 
have appeared to defend the cause but a british seniors group is 
fighting age discrimination 
europe is in the position to be the first to enter a new social 
world so what we decide to do is of great importance only now is 
anybody taking any notice of it says peter laslett a cambridge 
university demographer and expert on aging 
we cant look at it simply in terms of a burden says 
laslett 73 who likes to lace demographic data with lines from 
wordsworth on the joys of youth its an enormous challenge for 
human beings for the first time to use their whole potential 
demographers say that while the developing world will catch up 
quickly europe has more than twice the global proportion of 
elderly or 124 percent and northern europe has 25 times the 
world average southern europe with its higher birthrates is aging 
less rapidly by the year 2000 every fourth person will be over 65 
in western europe by one estimate 
the main reasons are lifeenhancing medicine and falling 
birthrates and some say europe has been slow to recognize the 
magnitude of the change 
were waking up to it late in the day says sally greengross 
secretarygeneral of eurolink age a coalition promoting the cause 
of the 60 million over60s in the european economic community 
france forbids forced retirement and job advertisements arent 
allowed to set age limits but other nations says eurolink age 
have yet to follow suit 
the 12nation eec plans a year of the elderly but red tape 
has postponed it to 1991 the eec budget for elderly affairs more 
than doubled in 1988 but only to the equivalent of 738000 
pensions are of primary concern prompted by fears of future 
workers paying hefty proportions of their salaries to support 
pensioners 
west germany estimates 40 percent of its population will be over 
65 by 2040 and its employers federation says employees would have 
to pay 36 percent of their salaries or double todays rate to 
sustain benefits 
the west german cabinet has proposed reforms including hiking 
the retirement age for women from 60 to 65 the age at which men 
retire italy is considering similar action most eec citizens can 
receive retirement benefits at 60 or 65 danes work the latest to 
67 and italian women leave at 55 
british prime minister margaret thatchers government has acted 
to abolish a 130 weekly limit on what pensioners can earn before 
losing some benefits at the same time it has been criticized for 
cutting pensions as part of what the government calls weaning 
britons off the dependency culture 
the elderly increasingly contribute to the economy by filling in 
for the shrinking numbers of the young already some are being 
wooed back by employers like britains tesco supermarket chain 
which hires 55 to 69yearolds 
theyre very reliable conscientious and dont need so much 
training says barry ball the personnel manager who began tescos 
scheme a year ago 
im not ready for retirement work keeps me young says 
doris broderick 58 who started working in a tesco market coffee 
shop six months ago after being laid off from serving coffee to 
lloyds shipping staff 
success after sixty a british employment agency for over50s 
reported a 60percent jump in requests from companies in the first 
two months of 1989 compared with the same period last year 
but prejudice still keeps many from working says the association 
of retired persons a british group based on the american 
association of retired persons arp which has signed up 25000 
members in eight months hopes to expand to france and germany 
the elderly are just beginning to organize in france said 
ariane revolbriard of frances 8yearold ministry for the elderly 
in germany a politician recently suggested a political party for 
those 60 and over 
southern european countries on the other hand have less use for 
older workers spain with 19 percent unemployment is studying a 
plan to offer tax breaks to companies which retire older workers 
early 
in the health field europeans are turning to home care to reduce 
strain on care systems and promote independence says anthea tinker 
head of britains age concern institute of gerontology and a 
specialist on elderly housing 
ing down for octogenarian novelist 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after writing 70 books 31 of them 
bestselling mysteries phyllis a whitney scoffs at any suggestion 
of quitting 
horrible what could be more boring said the 85yearold 
grand master of american mystery writers ive slowed down in that 
i only write one book a year a writer is what i am 
her most recent book rainbow in the mist was published in 
april its title inspired by rainbows that tower over the 
mistshrouded ragged mountains after thunderstorms have washed the 
sky around the mountaintop home miss whitney built two years ago 
not one to rest on her laurels miss whitney is putting the 
finishing touches on her 71st book the singing stones and 
researching no 72 i dont stop between books you have to start 
on new ideas immediately to have a new story start burgeoning in 
your imagination thats whats exciting 
miss whitney who last year received the mystery writers of 
americas highest honor began writing at age 12 i was going to a 
missionary school in china and the english teacher there encouraged 
me it went to my head and ive been writing ever since 
born in japan to american parents who later lived in the 
philippines and china miss whitney saw the united states for the 
first time at age 15 after her father died and her mother returned 
home her mother died three years later and the teenager moved in 
with an aunt in chicago 
i did everything i worked in bookstores and libraries read 
manuscripts and lectured she said of her ongoing attraction to 
writing 
she eventually landed a job as childrens book editor for the 
chicago sun and later had a similar job with the philadelphia 
inquirer all the while writing hundreds of short stories many of 
which did not sell 
her first hardcover success came in 1941 with a place for 
ann a book for teenagers miss whitney wrote three dozen novels 
including 20 mysteries for young people before settling in as a 
writer of adult mysteries with the publication of the quicksilver 
pool in 1955 
among the international bestsellers that followed were feather 
on the moon silversword flaming tree dream of 
orchids rainsong and emerald more than 50 million copies 
of her books are available in the united states and 18 foreign 
countries according to her publisher doubleday and all of her 
adult novels are still in print 
some critics have classified miss whitneys work as romantic 
suspense but she rejects that label its mystery suspense a 
whitney kind of book 
indeed rainbow in the mist about a clairvoyant who helps 
solve one womans murder and anothers disappearance has only a 
whisper of romance 
the protagonist in rainbow as in all miss whitneys books 
is a woman thats the point of view i have i feel more 
comfortable with it 
miss whitney herself was way ahead of talk of womens 
liberation ive always been a liberated woman i kept my own name 
through two marriages 
miss whitney maintains a rigid sixday work schedule i get to 
my desk by 9 and work until noon the creative process begins 
before she sits down at the typewriter she shuns a word processor 
because i couldnt think with all those mechanical things to do 
after lunch she exercises with a brisk walk on the deck that 
surrounds her home then takes a nap shes back at work at 2 pm 
and calls it a day at 5 
her time away from research and writing is as carefully scheduled 
as her work days her recreation consists of dinner out and a movie 
on saturday nights with her daughter and soninlaw who live 
nearby and watching murder she wrote on television on sunday 
nights i dont have much social life i like people but they can 
be distracting writers have to be disciplined 
her books have been so successful because i tell a good story 
i offer optimism all my books have happy endings i dont see any 
point in letting my readers down at the end im an optimist 
people feel that in my books 
miss whitney seems to radiate that quality her youthful spirit 
and zest for life belying her age 
im not old she said i dont have time to die 
</TEXT>
