<DOCNO> AP890710-0258 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
chase manhattan bank lowered its prime lending 
rate by a half percentage point to 105 percent today the second 
such reduction in as many months 
other major commercial banks were expected to follow suit in 
cutting the rate which is a benchmark used to set interest on a 
variety of consumer and business credit 
the decrease which was effective immediately had been widely 
expected and comes amid building perception in the financial markets 
that the federal reserve is seeking looser credit policies in 
response to a slowdown in economic growth 
shortterm interest rates in the bond market have been falling 
steadily as a result 
bond and stock prices were moderatly higher following todays 
announcement while the dollar was little changed 
if the current interest rates scenario continues it will 
benefit a lot of people especially those looking to buy a 
house said kevin flanagan a money market economist with dean 
witter reynolds inc 
because the prime rate reflects a banks costs of borrowing 
money including interest it pays on savings accounts or 
certificates of deposit it trails more subtle increases in other 
interest rates in the credit markets 
still the rate is watched closely because bankers use it as a 
basis for calculating loans to businesses and for determining many 
types of fixed and adjustablerate consumer loans mortgage rates 
are not included in that category 
the prime stood at 105 percent at the start of 1989 the banks 
raised it twice in february to 115 percent then lowered a half 
percentage point on june 5 those movements reflected changing 
concerns about economic growth and inflation 
the latest decrease puts the key lending rate at its lowest level 
since feb 10 when it was raised from 105 percent to 11 percent 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

