<TEXT>
an attorney representing about 300 depositors in a 
greek bank filed a lawsuit monday seeking 15 billion in damages 
and restitution for the depositors who claim their funds were 
removed from the country and frozen 
attorney constantine kangles said the classaction lawsuit filed 
in us district court would seek treble damages for us depositors 
in the national mortgage bank of greece 
kangles maintained that the bank used its us offices to prey on 
immigrant greeks by promising them high interest rates on deposits 
and that the earnings would be taxfree 
last month federal authorities raided us offices of the bank 
seized documents and arrested 14 of its officers on racketeering 
charges 
a bank spokesman monday denied the charges in the lawsuit 
not one bank account in greece has been frozen said the 
spokesman dimitris klitorakis speaking in athens 
the reports are incorrect not to say downright false 
klitorakis said he said the deposits have been transferred to the 
bank of greece the nations central bank and can be requested in 
the form of checks or remittances for any destination 
the only deposits that had been frozen were those made at the 
time of the us authorities raid he said 
he added that the number of people who had requested their money 
back was negligible 
barry slotnick a new york attorney representing the bank said 
all us representative offices of the bank were being staffed and 
that american depositors would have access to their funds next week 
the civil lawsuit against the bank and 14 of its officers came 
after federal authorities announced an investigation of the bank and 
the officers for racketeering on june 21 authorities raided seven 
branches in illinois massachusetts new york and pennsylvania 
seizing documents and arresting the officers 
the bank is charged with illegally accepting more than 700 
million in deposits from customers in the united states and sending 
the money overseas so the depositors could avoid us taxes 
according to a complaint filed in us district court in new york 
the national mortgage bank of greece is a separate entity from 
the stateowned national bank of greece which also operates in the 
united states the national bank of greece owns about 47 percent of 
the mortgage bank according to federal authorities 
in ads placed in greek language newspapers bank officers 
promised customers interest rates as high as 18 percent that would 
be paid in greek drachmas and would not be disclosed to us 
authorities kangles said 
he said about 300 people are behind the lawsuit but their ranks 
could swell to as many as 3000 the 15 billion represents treble 
damages based on an estimated 500 million in deposits involved he 
said 
the mortgage banks branches were not even legally authorized to 
accept money from customers in the united states authorities say 
rather the us branches were opened with the ostensible purpose of 
encouraging investment in greece 
mortgage bank says deposits in the united states were made at 
bankers trust and atlantic bank branches not at mortgage bank 
both those banks as well as mortgage bank are controlled by the 
national bank of greece 
</TEXT>
